## Learned User Preferences

- OCJS bindings PoC pattern: build a smaller symbol-subset YAML to validate the proposed approach with minimal-iteration builds before triggering the full multi-hour regeneration.
- Adding new C++ via `BUILTIN_ADDITIONAL_BIND_CODE` is a smell signalling the bindings codegen is missing the architecturally correct fix — try generic generator-layer fixes first before any manual binding.
- Pin GitHub/dependency versions to exact commit hashes for reproducibility; use `pnpm patch` for dependency patches, do not manually create patch files; when behavior regressed from something that previously worked, prefer config changes over code changes — find the regression; replicad source/replicad-opencascadejs edits in `repos/replicad` are in scope (close collaboration with upstream maintainer); fork remotes track upstream's primary branch — assimp uses `master` (not main), tinyusdz uses `release` (not main); push fork commits to the matching upstream branch name; never hand-write full SHAs from short forms — always run `git rev-parse <short>` to obtain the canonical full hash before pinning in CMakeLists/submodule configs (synthesised back-halves silently produce non-existent commits that break `FetchContent_Declare` at configure time); commit messages **and source code** on upstream/external repos must describe the change itself — never embed local research doc IDs (`R1`, `R5`, `R8`, etc.) in commit subjects, code comments, or python codegen rationale, since other contributors don't have access to those references (audit `bindings.py`/`generateBindings.py` for stray `R1`/`R6`-style cites when applying gap-analysis recommendations); the same rule applies to internal plan files, JSDoc, prose docs, and runtime source comments — never reference research codes like `Half-A R9 of blueprint v4` or "Finding 8" inline, only describe rationale (consumer-facing prose like "no client.connect() ceremony required" is also banned because it leaks internal narrative into user docs)
- Long OCJS builds (10-30+ min) use NX caching via `pnpm nx build ocjs` and dependent targets — user grants unlimited build time for sweeping bindings work, leave them unattended.
- When extracting domain logic into standalone packages, invert dependencies — the domain package owns its types/schemas, consumer packages depend on it (not the reverse); derive computed values from canonical sources rather than duplicating data across schemas; for runtime/kernel manifests authored as Zod, convert to JSON Schema during worker-side startup discovery so Zod instances never cross `postMessage` to the main thread; no backwards compatibility or deprecation paths for unreleased/internal APIs — roll forward with breaking changes (after a Netlify-style cutover, also strip all stale comments referring to the old approach so the codebase doesn't carry historical artifacts); do not add shims or adapters for consumers that don't exist yet; library-api-policy: no `void`-returning Promise-typed methods (always `Promise<void>`), no IIFE-just-to-consume-a-thenable patterns (`void (async () => …)()` is banned), no `await Promise.resolve(x)` where the awaited value is already settled (use direct value/rebind), no thin re-export barrels in `libs/`/`packages/` `index.ts` — consumers must import each symbol directly from its source module so deep imports stay legible (the rule is enforced workspace-wide and each package has explicit `exports` map subpaths rather than a single `.` aggregator); kernels must be fully self-contained (no shared cross-kernel schemas/types like `occt-shared-schemas` — each kernel duplicates its schemas to remain independently extractable); kernels treat a `main()` that returns `undefined` (no return statement or explicit `return undefined`) as a successful no-op with an empty `issues` array — never emit warning issues for missing returns (tests assert `issues.length === 0`, not "warning when undefined"); appearance/material props (color, opacity, metalness, roughness, density) live as flat top-level keys on shape return values — never nested under an `appearance` key — for parity with Zoo's per-shape `appearance()` and to enable future engine