forget" deprecations exist, paired with auto-generated `using` declarations replacing deprecated typedefs; `_SAFE_DEPRECATED_PREFIXES` and its derivative logic are completely removed (no JS-only deprecation shims — codemods handle migration of consumer code instead). NCollection container types are bound via auto-discovery + a generic `using`-declaration generator (NCollections are the explicit exception to the "no domain-specific patterns" rule; never add manual mappings like `BVH` or per-class hardcoded NCollection variants — every other type stays in the generic algorithm); `_resolve_stl_type` resolves `vector<T>` to `T[]` and concrete-length tuples like `[T, T]` for 2D vectors when the array length is statically known from the C++ template parameters; canonical templated strings are intercepted via libclang AST walks (not string-matching on `<` substrings, which is brittle and was rejected in review). `tarballs/opencascade.js-3.0.0-beta.<commit-hash>.tgz` is the OCJS V3 beta tarball naming convention; `replicad`/`replicad-opencascadejs` are repacked together at `0.21.0-v8.40` (lockstep version bump matched to the OCCT branch). Builds use `python -m ocjs_bindgen --filter <ClassName>` for single-class bindgen reproducers when isolating type-resolution regressions. OCJS RBV blueprint (`docs/research/ocjs-unified-rbv-blueprint.md` + the P0+P1 stocktake `ocjs-rbv-blueprint-p0-p1-stocktake.md`) wires return-by-value containers with an auto-emitted `[Symbol.dispose](): void` method ONLY when at least one of the container's child fields is itself a disposable C++ class (pure-data containers stay free of `Symbol.dispose` so consumers can use them without `using`/`await using` ceremony); the container's disposer is a shared `EM_JS` callback that iterates the disposable members and invokes each child's `[Symbol.dispose]()` — chosen over per-instance JS proxy wrapping because it is CSP-safe, Node.js 24 compatible, keeps memory overhead near-zero, and avoids V8's rejection o